title: Frame Braces for Imagine That Titian, Creality CR-10, and Afinibot A31

description.text:
Here is a bracing system for the Imagine That Titian, Creality CR-10, and Afinibot A31 3D printers. I took a little inspiration from the Wanhao i3 braces and directly used AzzA's ball design. All of the pieces will fit within the 300x300x450 build volume of that printer. You will loose approximately 12.5mm of vertical travel, but I feel the extra rigidity is worth the slight loss in Z travel. I have oriented the pieces in the way that I feel is best for printability and strength.

I printed the frame brace pieces in PLA just fine. They do not take a lot of heat.

Also included is Greg Hank's (Creality CR-10 Facebook user's group member) heated bed wire strain relief. I had my wires break at the solder a couple of times, and his strain relief looks like it will work well. I recommend you also print this in PETG for heat resistance.

BOM

Print one of everything except the balls. Print 8 of those.

50 - 5mm T-slot nuts.
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0197CCW20/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o07_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1

50 - M5-0.80 x 12MM Button head socket cap screws, allen head.
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01F7OK954/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o06_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1

50 - M5 washers

2 - 24" Lengths of M8 or 5/16" threaded rod and 8 matching nuts.

Settings

Supports: Yes
Layer Height: 0.1mm-0.2mm
Shell Thickness: =/>1.0mm
Infill: =/>25%

Edit 2-26-17: Removed Y motor mount. It doesn't seem to be any sturdier than the factory one. I will design one that works with the factory one.

Edit 12-3-17: Added STEP and F3D file formats so people can edit.

description.text:
Small desktop milling machine, from the concept to real life

Small desktop milling machine, from the concept to real life -Usable table of 5.5" x 5.5" x 4.5"
-65 In/Oz nema 17 step motors
-24VDC/7.5 Amp power supply
-High presicion NB Guide rails
-6 Micro stop switches
-Runs on MACH3 I designed this small machine to cut small PCBA and drill holes all in one single solution, as I was tired of using acid and then developer and then having to drill every single hole, process that not always went as planned, damaging pads and sometimes having to repeat the entire tedious process This machine was been designed to be made out of 0.5" and 0.187" aluminum, however my fist prototype was all wooden made, and it worked very good when making PCB, better that I ever imagine, so I did the inebiatle and tried to cut delren, to my surprise it did a fair good job, but I had to add a base plate to make stronger Second proto had walls and cross ribs made out of ABS, X and Y axes plates plus the sacrificial plate were all made out of 0.187" aluminum, and as on the wood description.text:
There is a couple of needle file holders and stands available. None of them matched my requirements:

  • Wall mounted, since stands use up space on the table.
  • Very easy to remove the files and put them back in place, thus no holes, or tubes, etc.

This is the Magnet Needle File Holder Mark II, a revisited version of Mark I. While Mark I was functional, it failed (for me) in terms of usability:

  • (too much) precision was required to get the tip of the file at the right position of the magnet,
  • the files had construction-conditioned play and weren't neatly aligned to one another,
  • risk of magnetising the file causing problems with ferrous materials.

So here is Mark II where the files are held at their ~3 mm diameter shaft just above the handle. There is a funnel to easily drop the file on the holder. The holder still uses magnets but their force is applied to the shaft minimising the risk of magnetising the effective area of the file.

Mild force is required to push the 8 x 4.7mm magnets through the 8mm channel; take care that you do not break the funnels on the flipside.
I used these magnets from AliExpress that are sold as 8 x 5mm (and are, actually, 8 x 4.7mm).

A toilet paper holder to be clipped on heating (21mm diameter, 18mm distance). The parts are connected with 6mm aluminium tubes (2x 120mm).

It is a proof of concept of a kind of printable spring. Initially I designed it for using in my Prusa Mendel, because the z axis springs were very difficult to find for me. Then I generalized the idea and parameterized the spring. These springs conceptually consist of a strip of plastic that is bended. The outer cross section of the spring can be square, hexagonal or octogonal. The spring parameters are:
  • fid (fold inner diameter)
  • folds: Number of folds
  • th: strip thickness
  • Drill: Drill diameter
  • Diameter of the outer cross section
    • Here there is a video of the proof of concept:
    http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbjiXFEyg_E

1.- Download the spring.scad file. Change the spring parameters and generate the STL
2.- Optionally you can just print the 3 springs given as examples
3.- I have used slic3r for slicing it. If the spring is small, it is quite difficult to print it. The easier springs to print are the ones with a square cross section.
4.- Print it!
5.- Before using it I had to file and clean the spring

title: Configurable Leatherman Wave Holster with Anti-lost Lock

description.text:
Holster for a Leatherman Wave and optionally the 2 tip cards (Bit Kit), Bit Driver Extender and/or a flashlight.

The configuration is achieved by combining the STLs of the central body of the holster with the right and left side STLs that are desired (see figure 1). Use Freecad, Autodesk Meshmixer, etc. With merge function.

The left part support for the flashlight is for the Nitecore Sens AA model. It will be necessary to redesign it for other flashlights. It can also be redesigned to incorporate other gadgets. Use STL named Blank or the FreeCad design as a support.

The anti-loss lock consists of a latch that takes advantage of the anti-locking of the Leatherman itself. When inserted, it locks into the sheath until the button is pressed while the multi tool is pushed up. This prevents accidental loss by moving or tilting the holster.

As a bonus there is a design for the Wave only, without accessories.

Notes:

  • The belt clip should be printed sideways to present the resistance in the correct direction once mounted on the holster. If printed with ABS, use PVC cement.

  • Once printed, pass the highest piece of the button (Button_int) through the hole of the holster out, and fit and glue to the small piece (Button_ext).

  • To remove the Bit Driver Extender, lever with the tip of the multitool (Image 2).

  • It is easier to remove the tip cards when the multitool is not in the holster.

Funda configurable para Leatherman Wave con bloqueo anti-pérdida.

Funda para alojar la Leatherman Wave, y opcionalmente las 2 tarjetas de puntas (Bit kit), la extensión del destornillador y/o una linterna.

La configuración se consigue combinando los STL del cuerpo central de la funda con los STL de laterales derecho e izquierdo que se deseen (ver imagen 1). Usar Freecad, Autodesk Meshmixer, etc. con la función merge.

El lateral izquierdo con soporte para la linterna es para el modelo Nitecore Sens AA. Será necesario rediseñarlo para otras linternas. También se puede rediseñar para incorporar otros gadgets. Usar como soporte los STL nombrados como Blank o el diseño de FreeCad.

El bloqueo anti-pérdida consiste en un pestillo que aprovecha el resalte del seguro anti-cierre de la propia Leatherman. Al introducirla, queda bloqueada en el interior de la funda hasta que se pulsa el botón a la vez que se empuja la multiherramienta hacia arriba. Esto evita que se pueda salir accidentalmente con el movimiento o al inclinar la funda.

Como bonus hay un diseño para la Wave unicamente, sin accesorios.

Notas:

  • La presilla para el cinturón se debe imprimir de lado para que presente la resistencia en el sentido correcto una vez montada en la funda. Si se imprime con ABS, usar pegamento para PVC.

  • Una vez impreso, pasar la pieza más alta del botón (Button_int) por el agujero de la funda hacia fuera, y encajar y pegar a la pieza pequeña (Button_ext).

  • Para extraer la extensión del destormillador, hacer palanca con la punta de la multiherramienta (Imagen 2).

  • Es más fácil extraer las tarjetas de puntas cuando la multiherramienta no está en la funda.

description.text:
This "artificial horizon" can be used in cunjunction with a sextant to practise celestial navigation at home. Just print the parts and get hold of a pair of plain window glasses with a thickness of 2 mm and 125 mm * 125 mm length and width (I paid 4 € for both of them at the local glazier).

Stick the two sides (they are identical) in the respective holes in the bottom part and fill the bottom with 1 to 2 cm of some fluid. A viscous fluid (motor oil, molasses) might work better, but even water will do. Then insert the two glasses into the guides on the two sides. These windows will stop the wind from messing up the fluid. You can improve wind protection by applying some adhesive tape to cover the remaining gaps.

Before you start working with your sextant please ensure that you have the appropriate filters in place, especially if you want to measure the sun. You MUST also take care that there is a filter towards the horizon as you will be looking at the reflection of the object! If your sextant does not provide a filter in the horizon line of sight one possibility is to darken the window glasses of this artificial horizon with appropriate filters. Please be careful!

Look for the reflection of the celestial body you want to measure on the fluid and then point your sextant to that reflection. Then bring your object down to this reflection and measure the angle. Subtract the index correction and finally do not forget to DIVIDE THE ANGLE BY 2 as you measured between object and reflection and not object and horizon.

Once you are finished, just take out the glasses and the two sides and store all parts in the bottom part. They fit in quite nicely.

Enjoy and help keeping this wonderful art of navigation alive!

Every time somebody calibrates motor steps with a 20mm cube a 3D Benchy sinks!

I made this object to reliably check the calibration of your steps, general inner and outer widths and fittings for square and round holes.

It is to big for continuous printing but this is required to have a reliable and "real world" source for measurements. It is not meant as stresstest. if this does not print well, you most certainly will run into problems with real objects!

  • The main cross structure is 200 mm x 200 mm with 40 mm wide legs.
  • The wide holes are 80 mm long x 10 mm wide.
  • The distance of the inner hole to the outer side of an arm is 15 mm ((40-10)/2).
  • The distance between the wide hole and the outer perimeter of an arm is 95 mm (100-10/2).
  • The center hole diameter is 20 mm and should be perfectly round.
  • The round and square holes are 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 mm wide.
  • The heights of the cylinder and cubes are matching their width.
  • The height of the whole cross is 1,6 mm.

The axis are labeled Y0 Y200 X0 X200 and meant to identify the orientation after the print finished.

The order of different elements is chosen such that you can measure it easily with a calliper.

The additional holes in the center are just meant for cutting the object into four pieces, because you can.

I hope it will help to check and helps to calculate your calibration for X and Y axis separately. Especially showing the difference in step (hardware) and extrusion related (flow / width) calibration. If your differences between different sized objects of one axis are not proportional to the length of the measured vertices, you can be pretty sure that it is not steps related. It also lets you estimate the sizes you need for a quick and dirty scale to fit.

To learn how to really calibrate your printer I suggest reading:

  • http://reprap.org/wiki/Triffid_Hunter%27s_Calibration_Guide
  • http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:52946

description.text:
A simple and foldable laptop stand that provides ventilation when using laptop on lap or soft surfaces. Inspired by a foldable booklets (http://www.snijlab.nl/?page_id=358), I wanted to create something that uses the same idea of folding wood, but making it a laptop stand instead. People are able to modify the design of the ventilation holes as well as the size of the laptop stand as laptop sizes varies. And because I was inspired by booklets, people may use this file to create other designs that uses the same folding/bending technique Materials:
1) piece of plywood (3.6 mm thickness)
Â· size: 60 x 30cm Note:
Â· Make tests of the fold to see how well it bends

A detailed instructions manual (photographic) available for download (Foldo manual) 1) Download the .SVG file or .AI file to edit/modify file to personal size + design
2) Set up laser cutter to cut file
Settings for the laser cutter (every laser cutter is varies so its good to test it out first)
Power: 100% Speed: 0.55
3) Remove all the unwanted scraps of wood from the fold and the ventilation holes
4) Fold the piece of wood in half (along the binding/fold)
5) Secure the fold by inserting the other piece of wood into the slots
6) Slide the small piece of wood to the longer indent to allow the whole piece inserted into the slot
7) Lock the fold by sliding the small piece of wood the other way around Points of Improvements:
Â· The fold/bind is still weak, still needs more revisions on the fold so then it can be sturdy while having the flexibility to bend at the same time. The folding pattern varies with the different type of material and thickness.

I made 2 important changes:
a) the knob design, substituting it with a numbers graduated one
b) the structure, created with M3x5, M3x20 screws and a M3*12 Brass Female Hex Hexagonal Screw Nut Pillar.

The nut pillar is put inside the plastic knob and the 2 screws push one againts the other in it. This way you obtain a rigid block that can rotate up and down in the M3 threaded hole of the printing plate aluminium chassis.
Now the knob has 9 printed numbers, and considering that a complete turn produces a displacement in height of 0.35mm, you'll have the possibility to perform a fine tuning. More with the numbers you can read the position number for each corner and save it. This way before printing you could check the height of the four corners simply verifyng if the knob position numbers are the same of the saved ones.
Now if you need to move the plate up or down you have simply to rotate the knob of the same number positions for each corner.

This is a slightly modified version of the Money Spinner by GeoffB. I had a lot of 20 euro cent coins lying around, and wanted to use those. This is a good way to put some copper coins you have lying around since your last trip to use.

Instead of selecting from a short list of coins, now you have to put in the size of your favourite coin directly. Look it up at Wikipedia, do a web search, or use a calliper. The pre-set size is for 20 euro cent coins. For the centre, you have to use a 608-sized bearing, i.e. 8 mm × 22 mm × 7 mm.

When you use euro coins, you can make yours a symbol of international cooperation. Mine is now using coins from

  • France
  • Greece
  • Ireland
  • Italy
  • Portugal
  • Slovenia
  • Austria
  • Germany
  • the Netherlands

Nine coins, nine countries! The last three are on the inside.

I also added the bearing caps from Arondite’s Fidget Toy Comfort Spinner

You may have to adjust your scale slightly to make the bearing and coins fit, especially if your printer is not calibrated too precisely. I had to use 102 %.

Included are three variants of the spinner as STLs:

  • One with three spokes for three 20 euro cent coins. This is the one i have printed.
  • Then i wanted it BIG. That can’t be made with the customizer, as the coin stacks are higher than the bearing. For that you should use 28 20 euro cent coins, in seven spokes à four coins. The one printed in red.
  • The last one is for Chinese 1 jiao renminbi coins, 3 spokes à 4 mao.

To install the coins, a vice comes in handy. Also one or two coins slightly smaller than the ones you printed the spinner out for. (E.g. 10 euro cent coins for a 20 euro cent spinner.)

I pressed in the four coins of one arm like this:

  • Press in two coins lightly, one on the top one on the bottom on a table with the palm of your hand
  • Put the smaller coins on top of these two coins and press in these four coins with the vice
  • Open the vice, the two small coins fall out
  • Put in the other two right-sized coins and press them in with the vice

Design files and history can be found at github, in a directory of my 3d printing repo there.

I had problems with the first version of the € 5.60 spinner STL file. I have now updated that. This version prints fine.

description.text:
YALE - Yet Another Lack Enclosure

I created these parts for myself because I was building an enclosure for my Maker Select and wasn't entirely satisfied with the other options available. This is designed around the typical Ikea Lack enclosure setup with 2 Lack sidetables stacked on top of each other. The 2 main printed pieces - "Leg Top" and "Leg Base" sandwich the upper table's legs and provide holders for magnets. The magnets in turn sandwich acrylic sheets to enclose the printer. I will likely add a handle to each panel to make removal easier, but for now I enjoy the clean look without.

My printer has this Z-Axis Mod installed. I used the "Z Brace" piece from dirtsky's Ikea Enclosure to further re-enforce the Z axis.

Supplies

Printed parts

  • (4x) "Leg Top.stl"
  • (4x) "Leg Base.stl"
  • (16x) "Magnet Cover.stl" (optional)
  • "Filament Guide.stl" (optional)
  • "Cable Guide.stl" (optional - flip it upside down to print)

Other parts

  • (2x) Ikea Lack sidetable
  • (4x) 16.125" x 17.5" acrylic panels (I cut the 4 panels out of this single sheet from Home Depot)
  • (32x) 0.5" x 0.1875" disc magnets (I used these from Home Depot)
  • (24x) wood screws (I used torx drive #8 1.5" interior wood screws for the vertical screws, and smaller phillips screws to attach the upper legs to the "Leg Base")
  • superglue (recommend gel)

Assembly

Start by marking your magnets so you know which side is which. I used a dab of nail polish on each after stacking all the magnets (so they were all oriented the same way) then carefully laying them out so that the same magnetic pole was facing up. Superglue a magnet into each holder (being careful to face the same pole outward on each part). This is so your panels are interchangeable - you don't want one corner repelling while the others pull.

Assemble the upper table by screwing the "Leg Top" pieces into the top of the leg and screwing the leg into the table - ensure the magnet holders face outward when tightened down. Screw the "Leg Base" pieces onto the lower tabletop, overhanging the outer corner by ~5mm (width of the outside faces). Stack the tables, ensuring the legs insert cleanly and completely into the base pieces - warning the fit will be tight. Insert screws through the outside faces into the upper table's legs to secure the two tables together.

Cut your acrylic panels to size. I recommend going slowly with a jigsaw or table saw to cut the acrylic. If you use a knife (per manufacturer instructions), you will produce a much more jagged edge and possibly crack a panel, forcing you to buy another piece - ask me how I know. Place your acrylic panels into the openings and superglue a magnet onto the panel in each corner to hold it in. (Optional) Superglue a "Magnet Cover" over each to clean up the appearance.

The "Filament Guide" is sized for a 1" hole so you can set a spool roller on the top of the upper table, if desired. The "Cable Guide" was created because I needed slightly more cable slack to mount the control box all the way forward below the lower table. It is sized for a 1.5" hole, with the center set 1" in from the edge. To mount the control box I originally used a part from another enclosure design, but found it too flimsy. I ended up building mounts with some scrap wood, gluing them to the underside of the table, and sliding the control box into it.

I had few (bad) filaments rolls that broke into small strands inside the bowden tube that leads to the extruder. i've decided to feed the extruder directly, bypassing the inner bowden tube.

After testing few prints, i can say it works great!

I've added a cone to the "BCN3DSigma - Bowden entry extruder" part and attached it back with the old screw.

I find it's much more easy and quick now to replace a filament with less friction, less time consuming errors and cleaning... - in short this is as close as i can get to a direct feed.

comments.text:
Usually i have the issue with breaking filament inside the bowden when the filament roll reaches his end.
The problem seems to be caused by the very small radius at the end. To solve this i put the remaining filament to another roll with bigger radius and heat it up a little bit (1 day summer sun or hair dryer). It works excellent and i can use the filament till it's very end. Anyhow ... i will also try this modificaton for the sigma because it should also minimize the friction from the bowden and in case the filament is breaking it's really a very good solution.

description.text: So this item was a class project to create an item made from 2 (though we used 3) items from thingiverse and then create one item of our own. We decided to take a new approach to our school's mascot the 'Duke Dog'. We attend JMU and so the first step was to find an appropriate Bull Dog, which we found. He was really cute, and so we then kept looking for a crown which we came upon this majestic one. It really fit with what our school uses for their own mascot. While looking around we found this iron man helmet and thought, wouldn't it be a funny rendition to use a marvel character's helmet for our project. The real irony of this whole project was that our project was made from wood filament, even though he is called the Iron Duke Dog. When creating the base, we spelled the word dog as 'Dawg' just to even be more outrageous for this assignment. When put all together he looks pretty nifty. Our first attempt the base was really small, so we have enlarged it for this print. The scaffolding was a little tricky to take off and the crown scaffolding was more annoying just so the pieces of the crown did not break.

title: rx5808-pro-diversity Case for Quanum Goggles
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I remixed my old case for the rx5808-pro-diversity receiver to fit the glove on the Quanum V2 goggles. I cut the stitching between the two pockets on the left side of the glove to make a single pocket. The receiver fits and the screen is visible in one of the openings.

The two halves of the case should friction fit together. I've had no problem with the case coming apart, but if you do a little hot glue should solve that, or remix your own. There are two versions of the back. One with a hole in the top for access to the programming pins (I added a right angle header with the pins pointing up for easy access with my USBasp programmer), and one with no hole.
